<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/kha_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/kha_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Chicago, Illinois 0/0/2002<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.40)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9813'>Andrew "Bee Boy" Sitte</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9813&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 11, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> *Many thanks to Voice of Law and Stormcrow for reminding me how much fun Chaos games can be*<br>
<br>
Last weekend, I ran a LotR tournament here in Chicago.  Actually, it was supposed to be a 1-deck MECCG tournament, but apparently I hadn&#39;t communicated that very well, and only one other MECCG player showed up, while 11 people arrived ready to go with LotR decks.  I decided that I&#39;d better run a LotR tournament since so many people were expecting it.  James, the other MECCG player, left, and since there was an odd number of LotR players I decided I might as well jump in with my MECCG deck.<br>
<br>
Against heroes I had a RotK deck, with Sam and Fatty backing up da King for To Fealty Sworn, an idea that I got from Josh Grace and Brian Wong.  The hazards were my own though - some boring creatures backup up by auto-attack boosting.  For minions, I wasn&#39;t sure what to use, but finally settled on An Unexpected Party, Dwarven Ring/potential dunk with AFor3 and Khamul engine/random creatures.  It was a barely tested deck, but I felt good about my chances; it wasn&#39;t likely to dunk, but it got out points fast enough during test runs.<br>
<br>
Round 1: RotK vs Hobbits/Moria Orcs<br>
<br>
I didn&#39;t really know what to expect in my first game vs LotR.  He bid 6, wanting to go first big time, but I rolled an 8 and was off.  I had a pretty decent hand -  Pallando at GH right away, and Fatty Stealthed over to Glittering Caves, where they found a Sapling.  He played Swarms and Armory on the way, but couldn&#39;t play any Orcs cuz of Stealth.  I Leaf&#39;d to bring in White Tree and Elves for Pallando.  His first turn, he laughed at me for going first - he didn&#39;t get Prancing Pony like he wanted, but got to start at my Rivendell, site 3.  Boromir joined his 4 hobbits, plus Bounder and swords.  Sam exerted for burdens.  He moved to my Moria, faced Pukel-men (Boromir took a wound and Pippin HS&#39;d) and I dropped a couple Nazgul perms.  He moved again, to The Under-gates.  Boromir played G&#39;s Vengeance to discard the Pukel-men.  Then I whipped out my favorite combo: Unabated, Tidings.  He was facing a 3@17 Balrog, and a moment later he was down to Frodo and an exhausted Boromir.<br>
My turn, I played Cirdan, SB&#39;d a bunch, dropped Gates, and grabbed both Quickbeam and the Elves.  Unfortunately, I&#39;d been drawing most of my SB&#39;d stuff, and didn&#39;t have any room to hold hazards for him.  He played Gandalf and scooted over to Lorien.  A Talent didn&#39;t do him any good, but I didn&#39;t have anything to play anyway.<br>
The low HL of Aragorn n&#39; hobbits kept them safe, but I had to burn Many Turns and Conceal to get to Minas T safely.  Pal and Cir went to Old Forest for Tom.  I was out of Turns, and with Cirdan in the company, Moria Scouts were free anyway.  He played 3 of them, plus Scimtars and a Marksman.  I wounded Cirdan for the archery, but he passed the BC.  Cirdan was only facing a scout, and crushed his strike.  Pallando, though, was facing 2 Scimtar&#39;d Scouts and a Marksman - auto wound, and the BC was an 11.  Craaaap.  Plus, I was still missing RotK, which I needed to start the combo.<br>
He had already built his company back up, and was heading to Hermit Hill with Frodo, Boromir, Arwen, Aragorn, and Gandalf.  Yow.  Choking Shadows and Tidings were laughed at by his buff warriors.  The Cave-drake coulda been nifty if he didn&#39;t have Son of Denethor to let Frodo just take a burden (his 4th) instead of being overwhelmed.  He moved again, to Bandit Lair.  Another Cave-drake, but he used SoD again.  SoD was facing the other strike, and without a booster, took his last wound.  I threw a Lure of S on Frodo to give him 2 more burdens. <br>
Cirdan was discarded, since I needed one more GI for him, pulling my points even lower.  Finally, though, I had RotK.  I stealthed and sat at MT, played RotK, To Fealty, Chance Meeting - Bilbo, Palantir, Align, White Tree.  Put me at 24 points, minus 5 from Pallando meant I couldn&#39;t even call.  So, I had to stop him.<br>
His final move.  I drew up, playing Balance of Things, bringing his burdens to 7.  Adunaphel tapped to send 5 to my discard - Mouth&#39;d The Will of the Ring.  Well, Frodo&#39;s Resistance is only 10, and The Will of the Ring reduced it to 6 long enough for Frodo to go insane.  So much for that.<br>
<br>
6-0, MP total 19-0.<br>
<br>
Round 2: Dunk vs Rangers/Nazgul<br>
<br>
I decided right away to go for the dunk in this game - after all, what could be more epic - one dunk deck vs another - er - well, vs a &quot;let&#39;s get 1/2 way to Mt Doom and call it a day&quot; deck.  My 2nd round opponent, Luke Donald, plays MECCG too, and knew that I rolled dice instead of bidding, so he just bid zero.  Learning my lesson from last game, I decided to let him go first.  He started Arwen and Greenleaf, and got RoN with the Pony right away.  Gwemegil & Ranger Sword too.  He double jumped to Rivendell, facing nothing at site 2 (Weathertop) but both Adunaphel and Khamul at the haven/sanctuary.  With their swords, RoN and Arwen were strong enough to just take a wound each.  It was about this time that I realized that my dunking was in trouble; I couldn&#39;t play The One Ring as long as his Frodo had it in play.<br>
My turn, I dropped An Unexpected Party, and was about to lay down 4 more dwarves, but I couldn&#39;t since I&#39;d started at Prancing Pony.  I Chance Meeting&#39;d one, held the rest, and ran to Moria, with the Scroll in my hand.  On the way, I faced Attea and Nelya - Nelya changed my Moria to his Balin&#39;s Tomb - where greater items aren&#39;t playable!  With a Risky Blow and a Concealment, Attea was defeated and Nelya only wounded/blade tipped Bombur.  <br>
His next turn, he got Aragorn&#39;s Bow, Sting, Thror&#39;s Map, and Boromir, LoG.  Sheesh.  He stung - I didn&#39;t have any orcs, but he saw Tidings in my hand.  On his move to Balin&#39;s Tomb, I dropped Doors, TNAA, and Ren & Uvatha perm.  I held the Tidings, forgetting about Thror&#39;s Map; for the first time someone actually used it at site 5, switching from Under-gates to Bridge.  Of course, I didn&#39;t have a balrog in my deck - but I did have him in my sideboard, which was good enough with a nazgul in play.  Ren stuck Durin&#39;s Bane in my deck, and he popped out, 2@18/9, +1 to bcs (18/9, fierce, +1 damage).  He didn&#39;t skip archery, but with 9 health that didn&#39;t matter.  Aragorn took two wounds, and Frodo Stealth&#39;d - and then I Uvatha&#39;d to send the &#39;Rog at them again.  THWACK!  Arwen was overwhelmed, and LoG was exhausted.<br>
I&#39;d drawn Gollum during his turn, so I stayed at Moria another turn to play him.  After all, he was my ticket to getting rid of Luke&#39;s One Ring so I could play my own.  He dropped a Blade Tip and Black Breath but didn&#39;t attack.  With his fellowship in pain, he moved to Lorien and stopped.  I replayed Uvatha and Khamul (thanks to TNAA).<br>
I shuttled my company over to Lorien, my hand now bursting with Dwarves wanting to join the party, and Gollum itching to get his finger through his preciousssss...  On the way, The Witch-king in twilight and normal Nertea showed up.  Nertea could have been scary, but Bombur had died to the Blade-tip that turn, so I only had 4 characters.  So, no big deal; have Thrain whack Nertea, sacrifice Kili to the king, and then use Gollum on the ONE.  Too bad Luke knew about Gollum&#39;s ability, and was holding a Fear.  No more Gollum.  Now what?<br>
Fully healed, with Gandalf and a Lorien Elf/Bow joining them, Luke double-jumped to site 8, using Archery and SoS to waste my Cave-drake and Sellswords.  He didn&#39;t even need ARV...  So, one turn left.  Great.<br>
I dropped a handful of dwarves, plus Gandalf.  I tossed 2 Longbottom Leafs, tapped Gandalf once (he had Cram), and split companies.  Balin, all alone, got a Master of E to Easterling Camp, while the Unexpected party hunted down the ring.  The party moved first, and even 3 fierce Nazgul weren&#39;t enough with a slew of scrub dwarves to take the strikes.  Ori and Fili died, but so what?  Balin ran to Easteriling Camp.  Still no One Ring in hand.  He ran back.  Faced Enquea, risky blow&#39;d, Dwarves Upon you - still died.  Oh, and still no ring.  One last chance - I triple Twilighted Doors, dropped FiF, and drew 2 - there it was, along with another AFor3.  Gandalf ate Cram, played 2 AFor3, and Frodo agreed (&quot;Take it from me!  You MUST TAKE IT!&quot;).  With no ringbearer, he couldn&#39;t win, and forfeited.<br>
<br>
7-0, Total TPs: 13<br>
<br>
Round 3: RotK vs Sauron<br>
<br>
Now, I thought Luke had a great deck, but this game showed me the real power of a Mr. Suitcase.  Not needing to start at Rivendell for dwarves, I went second.  He played the pony also, grabbed RotN to join OBH, LoG, and Merry FtS, and played &#39;everybody&#39;s friend&#39; Gandalf and Greenleaf.  Yeesh.  Then, he proceeded to move to my Weathertop, Pathfinder&#39;d to make it his Bree Streets.  I played 2 Assassins (my deck doesn&#39;t use FiF to protect the king cuz it Stealths/Cancels everything) but since his companions never have to tap for anything else, they cancelled most of the attacks and took 1 wound on Aragorn.  They moved again, to my Rivendell. Beorning Skin-changers - &quot;What, none of your characters are &#39;Warriors&#39;?  Awww, too bad.&quot;  So, he was back at Bree Streets, but he still had 1 more in his move limit, and that time made it to Rivendell successfully.<br>
Fatty Stealthed for the move to The Stones, while 2 Orc Bannershimmer play.  Fatty and Aragorn dealt with the auto, then Sam got Orcrist.  Halfling Strength and the rest of my Cram left Fatty with Glamdring after a Thorough Search.<br>
Hey, look!  It&#39;s Elrond!  Draw some cards...Old Toby...It&#39;s another stack of rares!  Arwen, Thror&#39;s Map, Glamdring, Aragorn&#39;s Bow, Elrond, Galadriel, Mirror (boo!  Yes, it sucks even errata&#39;d). He mapped to get the Waterfall, and was off.  Move to Moria?  No problem - H Intuition took care of the Cave Worm.  Move again, to Under-gates?  No, of course not.  Glamdring let him know I had Unabated/Tidings.  So, The Bridge.  Durin&#39;s Bane came out again, and I succeeded in shaking him.  Four whole wounds, wow :P  He moved again, to my Lorien, ready to ditch all the wounds next turn.  So, he tells me to discard Durin&#39;s Bane, and play other stuff.  &#39;Why discard my Balrog?&#39;  &#39;Cuz we&#39;re not underground anymore, duh&#39;  &#39;Well, my Durin&#39;s Bane doesn&#39;t say anything about discarding when he&#39;s not underground.  He&#39;ll march right into Lorien with you, thanks very much!&#39;  So, I was laughing as he got ready to face the &#39;Hog again.  Then he whipped out Gondor&#39;s Vengeance.  Boo!  But wait - wasn&#39;t it too late for that?  Sure was, regroup had come and gone.  So instead he played &#39;What Are They?&#39;  Huh?  Who holds that past site 4, let alone plays with it in the first place?!  Well, DB was roaming at Lorien, and he ran back home.<br>
All right, so he was at site 6 after 2 turns, and I had 11 points after one.  Pallando came out, squatted, and everyone else ran to Tolfalas to get a Sapling.  3 Orc Soldiers?  Seven prowess, no big deal...but that &#39;exert to wound&#39; thing was a bit of a problem.  Fatty Conceal&#39;d the King&#39;s skirmish, but Sam was wounded and Fatty eliminated, passing Glamdring to Aragorn.  Aragorn whacked the undead auto and found a Sapling, while Pallando still couldn&#39;t find the Elves.<br>
He moved to Hermit Hill the next turn, but I finally had some creatures.  Nothing much to hurt him, but enough to stop him (3 Nazgul and a Cave-drake, IIRC, plus 2 Rain-drakes on Summons - nasty with all Site 8s being Rivers).  <br>
I had Cirdan, and the Elves finally, but Aragorn and Sam had a rough time.  Still no Stealth, and with Hate Sam was wounded once, Aragorn twice.  Lucky rolls kept them both alive, but things were looking bad.  Then, they still had the skirmishes to deal with - but Biter and Beater reduced all of the Orcs health by one, killing them off.  RotK, sure, To Fealty, yeah - but my opponent had gotten Bilbo out the turn before, which meant no Chance Meeting, no White Tree, no Palantir/Align...ugh.<br>
He moved again, but only faced the 2 big drakes.  Oh, and a Wild Fell Beast.  He stopped.<br>
With no Tom for Pal/Cirdan, and my King wounded, there wasn&#39;t much I could do.  I ran to Lorien, but War Bands wounded and killed both the King and his bodyguard, leaving me at 2 MPs total, and I couldn&#39;t do enough to stop Frodo from getting to site 9.<br>
<br>
1-3, TPs: 14<br>
<br>
Round 4: Unexpected Party vs DPitTP<br>
<br>
I was already pretty exhausted after just three games, but at least there was only one round left.  After the close-call attempt at dunking in round 2, I decided to just stick with the main purpose of my vs minion deck - Dwarven Rings - especially since my opponent was undefeated.  I only rolled a 4, but my opponent only bid one.  I had to go first for Rivendell, but it turned out I didn&#39;t have An Unexpected Party anyway - just 3 dwarves.  I played Gandalf, and ran to Lorien, for another chance at AUP.  A Sneak, Armory, and They Are Coming.  Early on it seemed like everyone used Nazgul, but now Swarms are big (5 of the 11 players were using Moria).  Anyway, I killed the Sneak, but knew it&#39;d be back.<br>
My opponent started Frodo OBH, Isildur&#39;s Bane, and Aragorn RoN.  No Stranger to the Shadows and a single move made me realize that he was using &quot;Don&#39;t Pee in the Twilight Pool&quot;, or at least something like it.  Of course, that deck doesn&#39;t expect to go to Moria on the first turn.  Adunaphel wounded Aragorn once, and he was done.  I played a PBBW as well.  For the most part though, my nazgul were SBing for whatever looked useful.<br>
I stuck Durin&#39;s Ring on Rumours.  AUP, 4 dwarves, and Haldir all showed up.  After a bit of discussion, the dwarves voted Haldir out of the tribe, and he was stuck by himself to visit the Master of Esgaroth in the Horse Plains.  The dwarves and Gandalf got a Fellowship, and headed to Caves of Ulund.  Haldir died on the way back to Lorien (He&#39;d survived by Risky Blowing 2 Orcs at first, but on the way back even more joined, and he didn&#39;t have a chance).  With TAC, he got out 6 orcs, but I had 9 characters in a Fellowship, most with +prowess against orcs.  It was pretty clear that his swarms were going to be worthless against me.  I got the scroll and thorough searched a Fair gold ring.<br>
With a frown on his face, he moved on to The Under-gates.  I played a Nameless Thing plus Tidings - Aragorn tapped for one Nameless attack, and with Sting and a Stealth Frodo only took one wound, as did Aragorn with his sword and a Swordsman.  The 2@16?  With no body, a simple PATHS took care of it.  Then he said &quot;I&#39;m moving again&quot;<br>
Huh?  A Don&#39;t Pee deck moving again?  I mean, it was a smart thing to do with his hazards being worthless, but it sure wasn&#39;t to my liking.  I didn&#39;t have any more hazards for him at Lorien, so he took 3 wounds and a burden from Nameless Thing (after tapping Frodo for an attack again) and stopped to rest.<br>
After sticking a Lesser Ring on Rumours, my company moved unhindered (except for the 6 orcs they killed with a yawn) to Shrel-kain where they got the Men, 2 steeds, and a hound (AFor3 helped Fili be the one to bring in the Men).  I played another Rumours during my end-of-turn.<br>
Fully healed, Frodo and Aragorn crept out of Lorien towards Bandit Lair.  Frodo&#39;s Cave-drake was PATHS&#39;d, Aragorn took a wound.  Then I played a Call of Home on Frodo, and with no GI he&#39;s got to roll a 10 or lose his ringbearer.  Of course, he&#39;s using my dice, and they chose to roll their favorite number: 11.  Blah.  I tapped PBBW and tossed a River just to get it out of my hand, but since he didn&#39;t have a site phase it would have been playing a card for no effect, and I had to take it back.  He moved again but BSC held him back (that card is too powerful vs LotR).<br>
I ran to The Lonely Mountain, and the engine started.  I played a Precious GR, Wizards Test -  5, 3.  Yick, only a lesser!  Gandalf tapped for the Fair Gold, and this time it turned out that Gloin was carrying Durin&#39;s Ring.  He tapped, Bombur grabbed Emerald.  An Forth He Hastened, tapped again, Wormsbane.  I was at 28 points after 4 turns, but still hadn&#39;t cycled, and he was 2 sites from victory.  Crikey, what was I gonna do?<br>
He moved to site 8, and I Assassin&#39;d Frodo.  He took 2 wounds and Aragorn tapped, but that&#39;s it.  The Assassin was still out, but he moved anyway, and immediately burned PATHS to wipe out the Assassin.  Last chance to stop him.  I looked at my hand, the table, and the TP.  Discarded Daelomin for more Twilight, played a Thief.  Aragorn killed it, and I knew I&#39;d lost.  Another Thief, with Hoarmirath for a strike.  The Thief ran off with both Sting and Ranger sword - I had Uvatha in play, ready and willing to send a Thief back in for The One, but I needed one more Twilight to do it.  I laid down my cards and shook his hand.<br>
<br>
1-3, TPs: 15<br>
<br>
So, after 4 rounds I was only 2-2.  The top standings were:<br>
<br>
Me: 15 TPs (2-2)<br>
Jeff: 12 TPs (4-0)<br>
Luke: 10 TPs (3-1)<br>
Phil: 10 TPs (3-1)<br>
<br>
Unfortuntately, a couple people were upset, and forced me to redo placings with Win/Loss as the primary factor instead of tournament points. I ended up 5th. <br>
<br>
Highlights:<br>
*Frodo eagerly giving Gandalf The One<br>
*Showing how much scarier MECCG Balrog is<br>
*28 points in 4 turns, woot!<br>
*Cranberry juice.  Now there&#39;s a high quality beverage.<br>
<br>
Twilights:<br>
*Target-boy dies again<br>
*Having to abide by Uniqueness while my opponents didn&#39;t<br>
*Cranberry BLEND?!  It tastes more like rancid applesauce.<br>
<br>
All in all, I had a great time, and it convinced me to buy some LotR cards.  I&#39;ll definitely be sticking with MECCG for the most part though.<br>
<br>
-Andrew Sitte <br></font></blockquote><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php?id=3489&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
